      <p>Dominic Luthje: The Dialectal and Pronominal Differences and Similarities Between Dominican and Mexican Spanish.</p>
      <p>This project continues the work I began in last semesterâ€™s capstone course with Drs. Jennifer Cramer and Rust Barrett, exploring Spanish address terms and their use across dialects, regions, and countries in Latin America.</p>
      <p>I also expanded on existing research suggesting a link between sexuality and the use of address terms, particularly the pronoun tÃº and its social implications among men in countries like Costa Rica and Colombia.</p>
      <p>For this project, I focused on Mexican and Dominican Spanish, analyzing large corpora of Reddit posts from various subreddits containing users writing in each dialect. My main objective was to examine overt pronoun usage, hypothesizing that Dominican Spanish would show higher rates of pronouns like tÃº, yo, and usted.</p>
      <p>The website is structured into four main sections for this project: Overview, Dataset, Methodology, and Results & Interpretation.</p>
